Macedonia's Prime Minister Zoran Zaev, his wife Zorica and his son Dushko vote in the referendum in Macedonia on the country's name change, which would open the way for membership of NATO and the European Union, in Strumica, Macedonia on 30 September 2018.
Outside the Parliament of Skopje, Vladimir Kavardarkov, 54, organized a small stage and put out chairs in front of the tents set up by those who boycott the referendum.
"We are for NATO and the EU, but we want to go with our heads in the air, not sneak through the back door," said Kavardarkov.
"We are a poor country, but we have our dignity.
If they do not welcome us as Macedonia, we can turn to others, such as China and Russia, and become part of Euro-Asian integration."
